10.body: Welcome to the developer documentation for LeadsCalendar! This comprehensive guide aims to provide developers with all the necessary information to integrate APIs, understand the project's functionality, and contribute effectively to the LeadsCalendar project.
10.title: Introduction

11.body: LeadsCalendar is a web application designed to simplify event creation while incorporating payment processing capabilities. By leveraging the Google Calendar API, PayPal REST API, and Binance Pay API, users can seamlessly create events and make payments within the application.
11.title: Project Overview

13.body: The Google Calendar API is a RESTful API that can be accessed through explicit HTTP calls or using the Google Client Libraries. The API exposes most of the features available in the Google Calendar Web interface. Common Terms: Event : An event on a calendar containing information such as the title, start and end times, and attendees. Events can be either single events or recurring events. An event is represented by an Event resource. Calendar : A collection of events. Each calendar has associated metadata, such as calendar description or default calendar time zone. The metadata for a single calendar is represented by a Calendar resource. Calendar List : A list of all calendars on a user's calendar list in the Calendar UI. The metadata for a single calendar that appears on the calendar list is represented by a CalendarListEntry resource. This metadata includes user-specific properties of the calendar, such as its color or notifications for new events. Setting : A user preference from the Calendar UI, such as the user's time zone. A single user preference is represented by a Setting Resource. ACL : An access control rule granting a user (or a group of users) a specified level of access to a calendar. A single access control rule is represented by an ACL resource. For more details, refer to the Google Calendar API documentation .
13.title: Google Calendar API

14.body: PayPal APIs use REST, authenticate with OAuth 2.0 access tokens, and return HTTP response codes and responses encoded in JSON. Important Steps: Get client ID and client secret : PayPal integrations use a client ID and client secret to authenticate API calls. Get access token : Exchange your client ID and client secret for an access token. The access token authenticates your app when calling PayPal REST APIs. Get sandbox account credentials : The PayPal sandbox is a test environment that mirrors real-world transactions. For more details, refer to the PayPal REST API documentation .
14.title: PayPal REST API

15.body: Binance Pay is a contactless, borderless, and secure cryptocurrency payment technology designed by Binance. Scenarios: Merchant Acquiring (C2B) : Payment by QR code. Transfer or Send Cryptos (C2C) : Users can request crypto from others. For more details, refer to the Binance Pay API documentation .
15.title: Binance Pay API

16.body: LeadsCalendar offers the following key functionalities: Event Creation : Users can create events directly within the LeadsCalendar interface. Payment Prompt : Upon event creation, users are prompted to make a payment of 1 USD or its equivalent in cryptocurrency. Event Confirmation : Events are confirmed only after successful payment processing.
16.title: Functionality

2.body: Welcome to the LeadsCalendar project! This web application integrates PayPal, Binance Pay, and Google Calendar functionalities to streamline event creation and payment processing. This README provides an overview of the project and guides you through its usage.
2.title: Introduction

3.body: LeadsCalendar is a web application designed to simplify event creation while incorporating payment processing capabilities. By integrating PayPal, Binance Pay, and Google Calendar APIs, users can seamlessly create events and make payments within the application.
3.title: Project Overview

4.body: Users can create events on Google Calendar through the LeadsCalendar interface. Upon event creation, users are prompted to make a payment of 1 USD or its equivalent in cryptocurrency. Events are confirmed only after successful payment processing.
4.title: Functionality

5.body: Create an Event : Navigate to the event creation page and fill in the event details such as title, date, time, and description. Make a Payment : After creating an event, you will be prompted to make a payment of 1 USD or its equivalent in cryptocurrency. You can choose to pay via PayPal or Binance Pay. Confirm Event : Once the payment is successful, your event will be confirmed and added to your Google Calendar.
5.title: How to Use

6.body: We value your feedback and strive to provide the best user experience. If you encounter any issues or have suggestions for improvement, please feel free to leave feedback. Our team will review it promptly.
6.title: Feedback and Support

7.body: LeadsCalendar aims to provide a seamless experience for creating events and processing payments. We hope this documentation provides a clear understanding of the project. Enjoy using LeadsCalendar!
